ons/bottletr.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why people leave EQ</span><hr size=1> EDIT--I just reread this after posting, its rambleing and scattered. Im high on G's linctus and panadiene, home sick with a head cold.<br>
<br>
I quit a while ago at lvl 59.5 because the balance of what I had been sacrificeing for 2 years in RL finally became so large that I noticed it ( like everyone else here Im guessing, Im a bit slow). The feelings of addiction and unhealthy obsession where screaming at me. <br>
<br>
As for gameplay, sure the occasional conquest against terrible odds etc was still appealling but thats the exception rather than the rule right, the daily grind is, lets face it DULL.<br>
<br>
The balance of challenge/danger/conquest/time/reward stinks after 50. I liked exploreing, discovering new content basically, solving problems, eg how to get thru the xorb gorge at lvl 10..bloody fantastic fun. Those kind of nice bite sized problems, doable in a single play session just dont exist in the high end game, its all major drudgery, with more the feeling of trudgeing off to work on a chain gang than indulgeing in escapist fantasy fun, escapist fantasy fun was what I signed up for!, not what becomes increaseingly obvious, that this is a thinly vieled exscuse for drawing out your addiction, cough ..play as long as possible to maximise revenues. <br>
<br>
I dont begrudge verant there revenues, we all have to eat etc but the high end game stinketh, possibly by design. You never know they may actually have a social conscience and have designed in dullness on purpose so that after 2 years there addicts finally quit. Then again maybe not, perhaps they are just resting on there laurels. Personally my hat is off to them for what turned out to be an allmost embarrasing success, I imagine they sleep just fine at night, not thinking about there cult of player addicts and there wasted lives at all, the addiction is the players problem after all, not theres.<br>
<br>
Re the comparision between this game and other forms of addiction mentioned earlier, honestly I see little difference, the symptoms are allmost identical. There are very few &quot;users&quot; playing this game compared to the number of &quot;abusers&quot;<br>
<br>
I went cold turkey on it, Im happy to report from out here in analog land that life is indeed sweet. The lesson I learned from all this?  well its the same one I keep learning, or not learning it seems, that angle of view (perspective? subjectivity?)  is VERY important. Stare at the same spot for too long and you develop tunnel vision, unable to make other choices because you are barely aware they exist.<br>
Not to mention turning into a boring fart.<br>
<br>
I may yet complete my last 1/2 lvl to 60..its probably a small achievable goal..maybe..if its fun, then again maybe not.<br>
<br>
Abraxax<br>
The world is seamless cloth, dont expect it to fit<br>
<br>
PS  Wave to all my old pals, extended middle finger to my opponents.<br>
<br>
